{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-11-16","name":"Robert de Vaux VI","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Robert de Vaux VI","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Robert"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Vaux"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"VI"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1170–1235","fullLifespan":"about 1170–1235","birthDate":"+1170","birthPlace":{"address":"Gilsland, Northumberland, England","geo":{"latitude":54.9905,"longitude":-2.5732,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1235","userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Robert II de Vaux (died 1235) Baron of Gilsland, was an English noble.\n\nHe was the eldest son of Ranulf de Vaux and Alicia. Robert succeeded his father when he died in 1199. He married Johanna, of unknown parentage. Robert provided his mother, sister and his half brother Roland, as hostages for his debts with King John of England in 1212. He was made governor of the castle of Carlisle by John in 1215, and later joined the barons who took up arms against John. Robert was required to pay scutage for not attending a number of military campaigns of King Henry III of England. \n\nThere are records of his having been granted the custody of the County of Cumberland and the Castle of Carlisle in 1215/16 , and that he participated with the Barons against King John in the revolt that led to Magna Carta. His lands were seized by the king and given to Robert de Vipont, and then restored.\n\nIn 1221/2 he paid four Marks in Scutage for the two Knights Fees he held in Gilsland and also in that year he went on Pilgrimage to Jerusalem\n\nHe died in 1235 and was succeeded by his son Hubert.","sourceList":[{"title":"Complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kin...2nd edition Volume 9","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://dcms.lds.org/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE934237","sourceUri":"9N23-KBX"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth"